The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, January 21, 2004 				 Syndicate devises novel plan to prune wage bill
 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT																								Calcutta, Jan. 20: Syndicate Bank today announced an innovative voluntary scheme of special leave for two to four years for employees to reduce the wage bill and enable the staff to retrain themselves in the leave period. The bank also has plans to raise the Tier-II capital by Rs 100 crore with a greenshoe option of Rs 25 crore.																								The special leave scheme would be implemented from February 1. Employees who opt for it will be paid 25 per cent of their gross salary. And if they distributed financial products of the bank they would get incentives as applicable. 																								The voluntary scheme, with the bank having the final say in approval, was targeted at those who could not go on transfer and had domestic and mobility problems, a senior official of the bank said.																								Loans of the employees will also be rescheduled and they will be encouraged to undergo specialised training courses in information technology and marketing. The bank will reimburse the training fee.																								General manager (human resource development) B. S. Murthy said, This scheme will give an opportunity to the bank to reduce the wage bill and also get trained employees after two years. The bank employs 27,000 people in 1,845 branches across the country.																								Of them, around 1,000 to 2,000 employees were expected to opt for this scheme and the bank was expected to save Rs 50 crore annually from this initiative, said a senior bank official. Bank net up																								The bank has reported a 25 per cent rise in net profit year-on-year to Rs 305 crore for the nine months ended December 31 from Rs 244 crore in the corresponding period of last fiscal.																								The operating profit increased 69.2 per cent to Rs 665 crore from Rs 393 crore. Net profit would have been higher, but for taxes requiring Rs 184 crore, compared with Rs 70 crore in the corresponding period previous year. 																								The banks global business touched Rs 55,038 crore, a 23.47 per cent growth on a year-on-year basis. The domestic deposits at Rs 34,343 crore increased 24.29 per cent against Rs 27,632 crore. The domestic advances at Rs 16151 crore registered a growth of 21.68 per cent.
